We had to really repress
everything and be

00:20:11.200 --> 00:20:13.270 align:middle line:90%
afraid of saying persecuted.

00:20:13.270 --> 00:20:17.050 align:middle line:84%
And then later on science
comes, which was great.

00:20:17.050 --> 00:20:22.150 align:middle line:84%
But the way, I guess, in my mind
to understand science had to do

00:20:22.150 --> 00:20:26.890 align:middle line:84%
is if anything is not purely
physical, it's just rubbish.

00:20:26.890 --> 00:20:29.170 align:middle line:90%
And you can study it as rubbish.

00:20:29.170 --> 00:20:32.140 align:middle line:84%
And I have seen so many
programs, George, sharing this

00:20:32.140 --> 00:20:34.970 align:middle line:84%
here with you is so
important for me.

00:20:34.970 --> 00:20:37.810 align:middle line:84%
So many programs that I
could tell my experience.

00:20:37.810 --> 00:20:40.640 align:middle line:84%
And I could teach people
techniques to leave the body.

00:20:40.640 --> 00:20:43.360 align:middle line:84%
But I could not say
it's scientific.

00:20:43.360 --> 00:20:46.645 align:middle line:10%
Even at TEDx talk I did in
which I presented some--

00:20:46.645 --> 00:20:48.520 align:middle line:10%
>>GEORGE: Maybe there's
no science behind it.

00:20:48.520 --> 00:20:49.320 align:middle line:10%
>>NANCI: Exactly.

00:20:49.320 --> 00:20:52.390 align:middle line:84%
So even in that talk,
they go and they say,

00:20:52.390 --> 00:20:54.610 align:middle line:90%
oh, this is not scientific.

00:20:54.610 --> 00:20:56.320 align:middle line:90%
We cannot recognize this.

00:20:56.320 --> 00:21:00.100 align:middle line:84%
And I say goodness, I'm talking
about science the whole time.

00:21:00.100 --> 00:21:03.190 align:middle line:84%
And it's amazing
because if we do not

00:21:03.190 --> 00:21:05.980 align:middle line:84%
acknowledge that there
is a way to study this,

00:21:05.980 --> 00:21:08.950 align:middle line:84%
if we do not look for
methodologies for ways, then

00:21:08.950 --> 00:21:10.150 align:middle line:90%
it's going to be all lost.

00:21:10.150 --> 00:21:13.720 align:middle line:84%
But I guess this
natural capacity

00:21:13.720 --> 00:21:19.150 align:middle line:84%
that we have of leaving the body
is a lot now covered with fear,

00:21:19.150 --> 00:21:23.065 align:middle line:84%
because of these two recent
situations that we have,

00:21:23.065 --> 00:21:27.730 align:middle line:84%
like inquisition and
the science precepts.

00:21:27.730 --> 00:21:31.780 align:middle line:84%
And, of course, those who
can accept and acknowledge

00:21:31.780 --> 00:21:34.360 align:middle line:84%
their experience,
it's an exception.

00:21:34.360 --> 00:21:38.350 align:middle line:84%
Even in our everyday
life, not everyone

00:21:38.350 --> 00:21:40.240 align:middle line:84%
can say they have an
out-of-body experience,

00:21:40.240 --> 00:21:41.407 align:middle line:90%
not even to their relatives.

00:21:41.407 --> 00:21:45.320 align:middle line:84%
>>GEORGE: Does science even
try to explain what an OBE is?

00:21:45.320 --> 00:21:46.120 align:middle line:90%
>>NANCI: No.

00:21:46.120 --> 00:21:49.820 align:middle line:84%
The conventional
science really not.

00:21:49.820 --> 00:21:52.400 align:middle line:84%
>>GEORGE: Let's take a look at
Italian physicist and designer

00:21:52.400 --> 00:21:56.330 align:middle line:84%
of the first microprocessor,
chip Federico Faggin,

00:21:56.330 --> 00:21:59.780 align:middle line:84%
who talks about describing an
out-of-body experience that he

00:21:59.780 --> 00:22:01.170 align:middle line:90%
had.

